image.altText: gioldoglodgold

props.synopsis: Australia has won three gold medals in a stunning morning at the Paris Olympics, with victories in the pool to Cam McEvoy and Kaylee McKeown, and an historic BMX win for Saya Sakakibara.

title.children: Australian gold rush in Paris as McEvoy, McKeown and Sakakibara create history at the Olympics

image.altText: Anthony Albanese walks in a hat and sunglasses surrounded by Indigenous men in red garb and body paint.

props.synopsis: At the first Garma Festival since the defeat of the Voice referendum, Anthony Albanese will say his government remains "committed to Makarrata" as it beats a new path on Indigenous affairs.

title.children: Albanese points to 'best chance Australia has ever had' for Indigenous self-determination

image.altText: croweater on hill

props.synopsis: Australia joins the list of worldwide locations where Active Clubs have been established. Experts say white supremacy groups like this are a threat to our social cohesion.

title.children: Not sports clubs: 'Active Clubs' are threatening social cohesion in Australia, expert says

image.altText: A close up of the front of a small plane with a sunset behind

props.synopsis: Rex knew it was being ambitious when it expanded into capital city services after Virgin Australia found itself in trouble in 2020. Little did it know that four years later, Virgin would be the very company coming to its aid.

title.children: When Rex Airlines entered the Golden Triangle, it accused competitors of 'slot hoarding'. But what is it?

image.altText: A view of the coast in Beirut during summer time, which shows a bleu beach and greenery.

props.synopsis: Australians in Lebanon say they've been left "stranded" trying to exit Lebanon amid renewed advice from the federal government to evacuate the country. But many say they've been left in the dark after being told the airport is closed.

title.children: 'Stranded' Australians holidaying in Lebanon say they can't get home amid evacuation orders

image.altText: A black sign with 'CFMEU Victoria' written on it, hanging on a construction site.

props.synopsis: Construction bosses and building industry whistleblowers fearful of retribution will be free to speak out against the CFMEU under cover of a potential parliamentary inquiry amid concern existing workplace regulators lack investigative teeth and protections.

title.children: Fair Work takeover of CFMEU 'not enough' say critics calling for greater witness protections

image.altText: A man stands in a glass box as people take photos of him.

props.synopsis: One of the largest and most complex prisoner swaps since the Cold War was almost derailed by a shocking death, competing global agendas, and a US president's fading political ambitions.

title.children: A painstaking, top-secret prisoner swap was almost done. Then came a mysterious death

image.altText: Cattle grazing on a vast, dry outback plain.

props.synopsis: An investment company owned by the Canadian government gets early approval to take over the debt-plagued Yeeda Pastoral Company.

title.children: One of the Kimberley's oldest cattle stations set to shift to Canadian ownership

image.altText: A person filling a glass with water from a tap.

props.synopsis: Fluoride has been added to the water supply in WA's largest regional city, but those opposed to the practice continue to spend significant amounts to filter it out.

title.children: Fluoride added to drinking water in WA city, but 'rabbit hole' armchair researchers look to filter it out

image.altText: Anna at her gate close crop

props.synopsis: Anna reached adulthood believing she was an orphan. Then the truth came out.

title.children: 'I believe I was human trafficked': this Melbourne woman discovered her history was a lie

image.altText: hands holding Australian cash notes

props.synopsis: New data from the Australian Bureau of Statistics shows household spending has fallen by 0.5 per cent for June after two consecutive rises.

title.children: Australians households are spending less. Here's what they're cutting back on

image.altText: Saya

props.synopsis: After her historic BMX gold medal, Saya Sakakibara pays tribute to her family and reveals she had COVID earlier in the week.

title.children: Sakakibara fights back tears as she pays tribute to her family and reveals she had COVID before historic BMX gold

image.altText: Kaylee McKeown

props.synopsis: With her 200m backstroke title defence Kaylee McKeown becomes the first Australian to win four individual Olympic golds, while Cam McEvoy shatters the disappointment of Rio with Paris gold.

title.children: McKeown becomes first Aussie to win four individual Olympic golds, as McEvoy puts Rio disappointment behind him

image.altText: A composite image of a man in a puffer jacket, skiers, and a foot in socks over a fire

props.synopsis: The word on the street seems unanimous — it feels like one of the coldest winters in living memory.

title.children: Australia shivers through June and July, so was the BOM's forecast of a warm winter wrong?

image.altText: A composite image of Brittany Higgins and Linda Reynolds with Parliament House in the backdrop.

props.synopsis: The defamation action launched by WA Senator Linda Reynolds against Brittany Higgins and her partner David Sharaz is now underway in Perth. Here's how the first day unfolded.

title.children: 'Every fairytale needs a villain': Linda Reynolds staunchly defends role in Higgins saga, as it happened

image.altText: Steven May is helped off the ground by a trainer

props.synopsis: Melbourne is sweating on scans on Steven May's ribs after the star defender was forced out of Friday night's horror loss to the Western Bulldogs in the second quarter.

title.children: Melbourne star Steven May sent to hospital after 'incredibly disappointing' loss to Western Bulldogs

image.altText: Drone photos of the Kwinana big battery Stage One

props.synopsis: Like much of the country, WA is embracing rooftop solar with breathtaking gusto. But the state's position as the world's biggest island grid is posing a unique problem with authorities asking the question — how much solar is too much solar?

title.children: How the rise of solar power in Western Australia is a cautionary tale for the world

image.altText: A sign that says "Teen Challenge Grace Academy Grace Chapel".

props.synopsis: An alcohol and drug rehabilitation provider near Esperance vows to review its program after former residents raise concerns about its reliance on unqualified staff and limited mental health support.

title.children: Faith-based rehab provider accused of harming patients' chances of recovery

image.altText: CFMEU generic

props.synopsis: The Fair Work Commission has filed a court application to appoint Victorian barrister Mark Irving and a team of assistant administrators to clean up the beleaguered organisation.

title.children: Fair Work Commission moves to appoint CFMEU administrator

image.altText: A house has been destroyed by a landslide. Forest trees flank either side of a muddy bank.

props.synopsis: India and China have been the worst hit, as climate change intensifies monsoon-season storms.

title.children: Torrential rain across Asia leaves hundreds dead, many missing

image.altText: A tall blonde woman in a beige wrap dress surrounded by artworks: blue stacked totems and a brass wall hanging behind her

props.synopsis: Clementine Stoney Maconachie made her Olympic debut in the pool at the Sydney 2000 Games. More than two decades later, she's in Paris as an Olympian Artist.

title.children: Illness ended this Australian swimmer's career. Now she's at the Olympics as an artist

image.altText: A toddler in body paint dances against a colourful background.

props.synopsis: Amid shifting sands in Indigenous affairs, young leaders are drawing strength from their culture to stand firm.

title.children: A young boy dances in the pit at Garma as sands shift in Indigenous leadership

image.altText: Dyson Daniels of Australia holds his knee after slipping on the court.

props.synopsis: The Boomers are through to the men's basketball quarterfinals after results go their way, while the Stingers and Gangurrus are assured of advancing from the group stage after their respective wins in the women's water polo and 3x3 basketball.

title.children: Boomers avoid early Games exit, Stingers earn quarterfinal berth with win over Canada

image.altText: An RSPCA inspector puts an animal in the back of her vehicle.

props.synopsis: The charity says working in pairs in a FIFO model will reduce the risk of violence against inspectors, but animal cruelty advocates are concerned regions will be without coverage.

title.children: Animal cruelty concerns as RSPCA drops inspectors amid violent situations in north WA

image.altText: A young woman holding a baby, whose face has been blurred. A man sits next to them.

props.synopsis: The final week of evidence in the murder trial of Robert and Anne Geeves saw the court listen to more than four hours of scratchy audio and hear that police searched properties for Amber Haigh's body after receiving tip-offs from psychics.

title.children: Court hears of accusation of body being fed to pigs, calls from psychics as Amber Haigh trial nears its end

image.altText: Jack Robinson

props.synopsis: Australian Jack Robinson gets two shots at an Olympic medal after beating Ethan Ewing in the quarterfinals, while Tyler Wright loses to Caroline Marks.

title.children: Robinson secures two shots at a surfing medal after seeing off Ewing, as Wright exits in the quarterfinals

image.altText: Evan Gershkovich and Paul Whelan in separate images. Both are held behind clear screens.

props.synopsis: The seven-nation prisoner swap that saw three US citizens freed from Russia has been described as the "most far-reaching exchange between Russia and the West in decades". Here's why it's so significant.

title.children: The prisoner swap between Russia and the West shows how diplomacy, not law, governs exchanges

image.altText: Forensic officers near a small plane that has crashed in a field.

props.synopsis: After an inquest earlier this year, a Victorian coroner delivers his findings into a mid-air collision in 2020 between two planes in Mangalore, north of Melbourne.

title.children: Lack of communication between planes led to collision that killed four pilots, coroner finds

image.altText: A surfer looks frozen upright with his board in the air above a wave.

props.synopsis: From the pool to River Seine, see the magical moments for athletes from week one of the Games.

title.children: The most stunning images from the 2024 Paris Olympics

image.altText: Silouette of three workers on a ship standing by a hoisted large piece of machinery with horizon sunset in background.

props.synopsis: Mining companies hope to begin mining the sea floor for valuable metals soon — upping the stakes at a vote for the top role at the international regulator.

title.children: A high-stakes vote could decide the future of deep-sea mining

image.altText: Biden embraces Paul

props.synopsis: US President Joe Biden has welcomed home the three Americans who were sentenced to years in Russian penal colonies after secret "sham" trials and now free under a major East-West prisoner swap.

title.children: Alliances 'stepped up' and 'took a chance': Biden and Harris meet with prisoners released by Russia

image.altText: Mollie O'Callaghan, Lani Pallister, Bri Throssell, Ariarne Titmus stand and smiel

props.synopsis: Led by the two greatest 200m swimmers of all time, Australia has defied the weight of expectation to record a dominant women's relay win at the Paris Olympics.

title.children: West Australian Brianna Throssell helps Aussies to golden victory as rivals come together

image.altText: Kamala Harris, wearing a light blue suit, walks up an aircraft staircase and waves.

props.synopsis: Two weeks since Trump narrowly avoided assassination, the race for the White House is up-ended — and the Republican contender has long abandoned his short-lived shift to a "nice" tone.

title.children: As Trump questions Harris's racial identity, Democrats are trying a simple message: He and Vance are 'weird'

image.altText: Fighters in camouflage stand in front of a coffin with a large picture of Fuad Shukr displayed on the wall behind

props.synopsis: The leader of Lebanese militant group Hezbollah warns that the conflict with Israel is in a "new phase", as he addresses mourners at the funeral of a commander from the group who was killed by an Israeli air strike this week in Beirut.

title.children: Hezbollah leader says war with Israel has entered 'new phase' after killings of top militant figures

image.altText: A group of men celebrate at Australia's largest Indigenous gathering.

props.synopsis: A senior Yolŋu leader says a treaty between the Commonwealth and First Nations people will likely not happen for decades, as the opposition leader promises "no treaty" at a federal level.

title.children: 'I won't be here': Senior elder's prediction for treaty after Voice vote
